result.execSummary:
All charges against Wyatt Lee Eugene Collins in this case have been dismissed. These charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Wyatt Lee Eugene Collins is presumed innocent.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
10:08 AM Defendant Wyatt Lee Eugene Collins in court, in custody.  Attorney Lance Morgan Nelsen in court for Wyatt Lee Eugene Collins.  Attorney Chad C La Lor in court for State of Wisconsin. Court calls case. State asks to also call 20CF505. 
in 22CF126 count 1 amended to 946.49(1)(1). Court recounts charges and possible penalties. Defendant pleads no contest to both counts in 22CF126. Court informs defendant of rights given up by their plea. Attorney stipulates to a factual basis. Court accepts the Defendant's plea and finds that the Defendant's plea has been freely, voluntarily and intelligently made. Court finds Defendant understands all the rights they are waiving by their plea. The Defendant is found guilty and Judgment of Conviction is entered. All remaining files dismissed, on 20CF505 Judgment of Conviction entered on count 1, found guilty. 22CF182 and 2CF139 are dismissed.
State makes statements and cites prior convictions. 
Defendant makes statements.
Court orders on 20CF505, 9 months jail, concurrent to 21CF438, 3 credit, 50 fine plus costs, 
on 22CF126, 120 days jail each count, concurrent, consecutive to 20CF505, 50 fine plus costs, bail applied. Sentence credit will be worked out between parties.

3:24 PM Defendant Wyatt Lee Eugene Collins appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Angela Wilson in court for State of Wisconsin. Attorney Lance Nelsen appears via video appearance on behalf of the defendant. Attorney Nelsen acknowledges receipt of the complaint and waives reading. State asks for $3,000 cash and no use of controlled substances. State indicates that he is on probation hold and has a pending case in MN. State notes defendant's open files in Douglas County and in MN and recites cash bails posted in each case. Felony warrant issued on May 13 from MN. Attorney Nelsen indicates that he is a Superior resident and has family in Superior. Indicates that there is DJOC in one of the open felony matters. Does not think that he will miss court appearances and notes that MN has interest in the defendant. Court notes concerns over open cases and felony warrant. Notes that other cash bails have not stopped the defendant from allegedly committing more crimes. Court orders $3,000 cash with conditions of no use or possession of drugs or controlled substances. Defendant indicates that he is trying to get his life back together, notes health concerns and has been in contact with treatment center.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for June 1, 2022 at 11:00 am.
